of the Third World that once embraced ideologies of state-centered radical change. Malley focuses on the interplay between politics, economics, and ideology to explain the rise, essential components, and precipitous decline of Third Worldism—a movement that attracted scholars and activists in both the developed and underdeveloped worlds from the mid 1950s to the mid 1980s. He relates the disillusionment with Third Worldism to the growing appeal in the Third World of economic liberalism, versions of political pluralism, and ideological movements that threaten the very existence of the central state.At a time when the public increasingly is associating countries of the less developed world with Islamism, tribalism, and ethnic warfare, The Call from Algeria challenges our assumptions and offers a new perspective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIslam and politicsxAlgeria. 0aIslam and politicszAlgeria. 7aHISTORY / Africa / General.2bisacsh  a20th century algerian history.  a20th century algerian politics.  a20th century global politics.  aactivism.  aafrican history.  aalgeria.  aalgerian history.  aalgerian politics.  acivil war.  acold war.  adisillusionment.  aeconomic liberalism.  aeconomics.  aethnic warfare.  aideology.  aislam.  aislamic battleground.  aislamism.  apolitical pluralism.  apolitics.  apostcolonialism.  areligion.  arevolution.  arevolutionary socialism.  asocialism.  asoviet union.  astate centered radical change.  athird worldism.  athree world model.  atribalism.  aunited states of america.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052020301340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520917026?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/97805